The risks of being a single parent in Slovakia are manifold, and they wait for women in this situation at every stage of their lives. Most single mothers remain poverty-stricken, ill-treated in social contexts, having been unemployed for a long time.

Lifestyle

Historically, Slovak society has endeavoured to limit the number of children among the poor. When a situation of poverty arises, many women have to choose between marriage and motherhood. Divorce and single motherhood are a dilemma because it usually goes against traditional views and a woman faces an additional burden of stigma as a result of losing her family. A single woman, whether divorced or a widow, has traditionally been condemned as a social outcast.

Slovak law still does not ensure adequate opportunities for women during pregnancy and in child rearing, particularly when in the situation of poverty. Without significant financial support provided by patriarchal Czechoslovak society, women were compelled to follow family traditions and their own cultural background and beliefs, placing priority on marriage and child rearing.
